{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Layer Normalization Does"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Layer normalization (Ba et al. 2016) standardises a vector's values to have zero mean and unit variance, then rescales with learned parameters. For a d_model-dimensional vector x from a single token:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{LN}(x) = \\gamma \\cdot \\frac{x - \\mu}{\\sqrt{\\sigma^2 + \\varepsilon}} + \\beta"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "where μ and σ² are the mean and variance computed across the d_model dimensions of that one token's vector. γ (gain) and β (bias) are learned vectors of shape (d_model,) — one scalar per dimension. ε is a small constant (typically 1e-5) that prevents division by zero."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Layer normalization diagram: a 6-dim token vector is normalised to zero mean and unit variance, then scaled by gamma and shifted by beta. Right side shows BatchNorm normalises across the batch dimension while LayerNorm normalises across the feature dimension per token, plus RMSNorm comparison."}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Layer Norm vs Batch Norm"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Batch normalization (Ioffe & Szegedy 2015) computes statistics over the batch dimension for each feature. Layer normalization computes them over the feature dimension for each example. This distinction is critical for transformers:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Variable sequence lengths:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Batch norm needs the same sequence length across examples in a batch. Layer norm operates per-token and is length-agnostic."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Small batch sizes:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Batch norm statistics become unreliable with few examples. LLM training often uses small per-device batches; layer norm statistics are exact regardless of batch size."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "No running statistics at inference:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Batch norm tracks running mean/variance during training and uses them at inference. Layer norm recomputes statistics from each input — simpler and no train/inference discrepancy."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "PyTorch Implementation"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n# Built-in: normalises over the last dimension by default\nln = nn.LayerNorm(normalized_shape=512)  # d_model = 512\n\nx = torch.randn(2, 16, 512)  # (batch, seq_len, d_model)\ny = ln(x)\nprint(y.shape)   # torch.Size([2, 16, 512])\n\n# Learnable parameters\nprint(ln.weight.shape)  # torch.Size([512]) — gamma\nprint(ln.bias.shape)    # torch.Size([512]) — beta\n\n# Initialisation: gamma=1, beta=0 → identity at start\nprint(ln.weight.mean().item())  # 1.0\nprint(ln.bias.mean().item())    # 0.0\n\n# Manual implementation to make the formula concrete\ndef layer_norm_manual(x, gamma, beta, eps=1e-5):\n    mu    = x.mean(dim=-1, keepdim=True)         # mean over d_model\n    sigma = x.var(dim=-1, keepdim=True, unbiased=False)  # variance over d_model\n    x_hat = (x - mu) / (sigma + eps).sqrt()      # normalise\n    return gamma * x_hat + beta\n\n# Both should give the same result\nx_single = torch.randn(4, 512)\ngamma = torch.ones(512)\nbeta  = torch.zeros(512)\ny_manual = layer_norm_manual(x_single, gamma, beta)\ny_builtin = nn.LayerNorm(512)(x_single)\nprint(torch.allclose(y_manual, y_builtin, atol=1e-5))  # True"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "RMSNorm: The Modern Simplification"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Root Mean Square Layer Normalization (Zhang & Sennrich 2019) drops the mean-centering step, keeping only the root-mean-square scaling and the gain γ:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{RMSNorm}(x) = \\frac{x}{\\text{RMS}(x)} \\cdot \\gamma, \\qquad \\text{RMS}(x) = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{d}\\sum_{i=1}^{d} x_i^2 + \\varepsilon}"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "No bias β. No mean subtraction. Zhang & Sennrich showed that re-centering contributes little to training stability while adding compute cost. RMSNorm is 15–20% faster than LayerNorm and is the default in LLaMA 1/2/3, Mistral, Falcon, and Gemma."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nclass RMSNorm(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, eps: float = 1e-6):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.eps = eps\n        self.gamma = nn.Parameter(torch.ones(d_model))\n\n    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:\n        # RMS over last dimension\n        rms = x.pow(2).mean(dim=-1, keepdim=True).add(self.eps).sqrt()\n        return self.gamma * x / rms\n\n\n# Usage\nrms_norm = RMSNorm(d_model=4096)\nx = torch.randn(1, 32, 4096)\ny = rms_norm(x)\nprint(y.shape)   # torch.Size([1, 32, 4096])\n\n# LLaMA uses this before every sublayer (pre-norm)\n# Equivalent to torch's built-in starting from PyTorch 2.4:\n# nn.RMSNorm(4096, eps=1e-6)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why Normalisation Stabilises Training"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Without normalisation, activations can grow or shrink exponentially as they pass through many layers. Consider a 24-layer transformer: if each FFN multiplies the signal by 1.1 on average, activations grow by 1.1²⁴ ≈ 9.8× before the loss. Conversely, if each layer shrinks the signal by 0.9, activations are down to 0.9²⁴ ≈ 0.08. Normalisation after each sublayer (post-norm) or before each sublayer (pre-norm) keeps the magnitude of activations controlled:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Stable gradient magnitudes:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Normalised activations keep gradient scales consistent across layers, enabling larger learning rates."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Regularisation effect:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Re-centering and rescaling reduce the model's sensitivity to weight initialisation and learning rate choice."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "γ and β give flexibility back:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " After normalising to mean-zero / unit-variance, the learned gain and bias can re-scale and re-shift any dimension independently. The network is not forced to keep the normalised scale."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Verifying Normalisation Properties"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nln = nn.LayerNorm(512)\nx  = torch.randn(32, 16, 512) * 100   # large magnitude input\ny  = ln(x)\n\n# After LN, each token vector should have mean≈0 and std≈1\nprint(y.mean(dim=-1).abs().max().item())   # < 1e-5  (near-zero mean)\nprint(y.std(dim=-1).mean().item())         # ≈ 1.0   (unit std)\n\n# The learnable gamma and beta are NOT applied here (they are 1 and 0 at init)\n# After training, they deviate from identity:\n# gamma may become e.g. 0.5 for some dims, 1.8 for others\n# This lets the network re-weight which features are emphasised."}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key insight:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Layer normalization is the glue that makes deep transformer stacks trainable. By normalising each token's representation independently across features, it keeps activation magnitudes stable regardless of depth, batch size, or sequence length. RMSNorm drops the mean-centering step without loss of performance, making it the preferred choice in modern LLMs."}]}]}]}}